aws::graph::propositions: # Mooney M20C Airplane Engine Power Loss Incident
A Mooney M20C airplane with registration number N6474U lost engine power shortly after takeoff.
The incident occurred on January 17, 2015, at approximately 1630 central standard time.
The incident occurred after departing a private airstrip in Lonoke County, Arkansas.
The pilot held an airline transport rating.
The pilot was not injured in the incident.
The airplane was substantially damaged in the incident.
The airplane was registered to a private individual.
The airplane was operated by a private individual.
The flight was conducted under the provisions of 14 Code of Federal Regulations Part 91.
The flight was classified as a personal flight.
Visual meteorological conditions prevailed at the time of the accident.
The pilot performed an engine run-up before takeoff.
The engine instruments showed readings within normal operating range during run-up.
The pilot retracted the landing gear after takeoff.
The engine lost power shortly after the gear retraction.
The pilot immediately applied carburetor heat after the power loss.
The carburetor heat application resulted in only a moment of partial power restoration.
The pilot selected a nearby highway for the forced landing.
The airplane collided with several trees before reaching the highway.
The airplane came to rest upright on its belly.
A Federal Aviation Administration inspector responded to the incident.
The inspector noted extensive damage to the right wing.
The inspector noted extensive damage to the forward section of the fuselage.
An inspection of the fuel tank filler ports was conducted.
Fuel was not visible in the right fuel tank.
Approximately half-inch of fuel was visible in the left fuel tank.
The National Transportation Safety Board Investigator-In-Charge examined the engine.
The engine was rotated by hand during examination.
A thumb compression test was performed on each cylinder.
Engine continuity was confirmed to the accessory drive section.
Valve train continuity was confirmed to the accessory drive section.
The magnetos produced a spark at each sparkplug terminal.
The electric-driven fuel pump operated when electrical power was supplied.
The carburetor heat control cable was broken.
The carburetor heat control cable was not attached to its respective point.
The mixture control cable was broken.
The mixture control cable was not attached to its respective point.
For attachment to the carburetor's mixture control arm, the cable end had been wrapped around the attachment's bolt.
The mixture control cable's break was located under the bolt head.
The mixture control cable's break had both a dull and a shiny section.
The mixture control arm was attached to the carburetor.
The mixture control arm would remain at whichever position it was placed.
The defining event of the incident was loss of total engine power.
Fuel starvation occurred during the flight.

text:
# Factual Information

## History of Flight

| | |
|-|-|
| Takeoff | Fuel starvation |
| Initial climb | Loss of engine power (total) (Defining event) |
| Emergency descent | Off-field or emergency landing |

On January 17, 2015, about 1630 central standard time, a Mooney M20C airplane, N6474U, lost engine power shortly after departing a private airstrip in Lonoke County, Arkansas. The airline transport rated pilot was not injured and the airplane was substantially damaged. The airplane was registered to and operated by a private individual under the provisions of the 14 Code of Federal Regulations Part 91 as a personal flight. Visual meteorological conditions prevailed at the time of the accident.

The pilot reported that he performed an engine a run-up with the engine instruments; everything was in the normal operating range. Just after takeoff, he retracted the gear, and shortly thereafter, the engine lost power. He immediately applied carburetor heat; however, he only got a moment of partial power back. The pilot then selected a nearby highway for the forced landing. The airplane collided with several trees just short of the highway, before coming to rest upright on its belly. The responding Federal Aviation Administration inspector, noted extensive damage to the right wing, and forward section of the fuselage. A inspection of the fuel tank filler ports revealed, fuel was not visible in the right fuel tank and about half-inch of fuel was visible in the left fuel tank.

An examination of the engine was conducted by the NTSB IIC. The engine was rotated by hand; a thumb compression test was done on each cylinder. Engine and valve train continuity was confirmed to the accessory drive section. The magnetos produced a spark at each sparkplug terminal. The electric-driven fuel pump operated, when electrical power was supplied. Both the carburetor heat and mixture control cables were broken and not attached to their respective points. For attachment to the carburetor's mixture control arm, the cable end had been wrapped around the attachment's bolt. The cable's break, which was located under the bolt head, had both a dull and a shiny section. The mixture control arm attached to the carburetor, and would remain at whichever position it was placed.
